{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}} {{Refimprove|date=April 2011}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Abdelaziz Ben Tifour | image =Abdelaziz-Ben-Tifour.jpg | caption = | fullname = Abdelaziz Ben Tifour | birth_date = {{birth date|1927|07|25|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Hussein Dey District|Hussein Dey]], [[Algeria]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1970|11|19|1927|07|25|df=y}} | death_place = [[Algiers]], [[Algeria]] | height = {{height|m=1.74|precision=0}} | position = [[Midfield (association football)|Midfield]] | years1 = 1945–1946 | clubs1 = [[Espérance Sportive de Tunis|Espérance Tunis]] | caps1 = – | goals1 = – | years2 = 1946–1948 | clubs2 = [[Club Sportif de Hammam-Lif|CS Hammam-Lif]] | caps2 = – | goals2 = – | years3 = 1948–1953 | clubs3 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]] | caps3 = 129 | goals3 = 34 | years4 = 1953–1955 | clubs4 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] | caps4 = 65 | goals4 = 15 | years5 = 1955–1958 | clubs5 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] | caps5 = 86 | goals5 = 13 | years6 = 1962–1963 | clubs6 = [[USM Alger]] | caps6 = – | goals6 = – | nationalyears1 = 1952–1957 | nationalteam1 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalyears2 = 1958–1962 | nationalteam2 = [[FLN football team|FLN]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalcaps2 = - | nationalgoals2 = - | manageryears1 = 1959–1962 | managerclubs1 = [[FLN football team|FLN]] | manageryears2 = 1961–1962 | managerclubs2 = US Tunis | manageryears3 = 1969 | managerclubs3 = [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] | manageryears4 = 1969–1970 | managerclubs4 = [[JS Kabylie]] }}
'''Abdelaziz Ben Tifour''' ({{lang-ar|'''عبدالعزيز بن طيفور'''}}; {{birth date|1927|07|25|df=y}} – {{death date|1970|11|19|df=y}}) was a professional [[France|French]]-[[Algeria]]n [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].
==Life and career== He was a pioneer of Algerian football playing in Tunisia and France in the 40s and 50s as well as establishing the first Algerian national team with two other [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|FLN]] activists featuring ten players in France’s provisional World Cup squad on the eve of the finals in Sweden.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} One of those players was Ben Tifour himself, who had played for the [[France national football team|French national team]] on four occasions including one appearance at the 1954 World Cup.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}
Born in [[Hussein Dey District|Hussein-Dey]]. In the summer of 1948, he moved to Europe to play for French first division club [[OGC Nice]], making his debut in a 1–1 draw with [[Red Star Paris]] and by the time Ben Tifour played at the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]] in Switzerland in a 3–2 win over [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]; he had already won two league titles and a [[Coupe de France|French Cup]] with [[OGC Nice]]. He moved to [[Troyes AC]] after six seasons with Nice in 1954 and then signed for [[AS Monaco]] in 1956, which would be his last club in Europe. In total, he made 280 appearances in the [[Ligue 1|French top division]], scoring 62 goals.<ref>{{NFT player|id=29306|name=Abdelaziz Ben Tifour|accessdate=14 April 2011}}</ref> He returned to [[Tunis]] in 1958 to form the [[Algeria national football team|FLN Algerian national team]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}
When Algeria was granted independence in 1962, the 33-year-old Ben Tifour unlike Mekloufi and [[Ahmed Oudjani]] who moved back to play in Europe, returned to his homeland to take up a player-coach role at [[USM Alger]] leading them to the first Algerian championship in 1963.
Ben Tifour died at the age of only 43 while he was coach at [[JS Kabylie]] during the 1970–1971 season.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}
==Clubs== *[[Espérance Sportive de Tunis]] (1945–1946) *Club Sportif de Hammam Lif (1946–1948) *[[OGC Nice]] (1948–1954) *[[Troyes AC|Association Sportive Troyenne Savinienne]] (1954–1956) *[[AS Monaco]] (1956–1958) *FLN Equipe (1958–1962) *USMA, Union Sportive de la Medina d'Alger (1962–1963)
