{{Infobox person |name = Clément Cormier |image = |alt = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1910|01|15}} |birth_place = Moncton, New Brunswick |death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|07|28|1910|01|15}} |death_place = |other_names = |known_for = |occupation = |nationality = }} Father '''Clément Cormier''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CC}} (January 15, 1910 &ndash; July 28, 1987) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] priest, academic and the vice chancellor and founder of [[Université de Moncton]].
Born in [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]], the son of Clément Cormier and Léontine Breau, he received a Bachelor of Arts in 1931, from [[University of St. Joseph's College|Université Saint-Joseph]]. He was ordained in 1936. In 1940 he received another Bachelor's degree from [[Université Laval]]. From 1948 until 1953, he was the [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of Université Saint-Joseph. From 1973 until 1978, he was the Chancellor of the Université de Moncton.
In 1967 he was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] and was promoted to Companion in 1972.
==References== * {{cite web | title=FONDS CLÉMENT-CORMIER, C.S.C. (1910-1987) (in French) | work=Université de Moncton | url=https://www.umoncton.ca/etudeacadiennes/centre/etatgen/etat100/p0177.html | accessdate=May 16, 2005}} * {{Canadian honour|Type=orc|ID=1897|accessdate=26 May 2010}}
