{{DEFAULTSORT:Cormier, Clement}} [[Category:1910 births]] [[Category:1987 deaths]] [[Category:Acadian people]] [[Category:Canadian clergy]] [[Category:Canadian university and college chancellors]] [[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]] [[Category:People from Moncton]] [[Category:Université Laval alumni]]

This is a genealogical tree of the leaders of the '''[[Fujiwara clan]]''' from 669 to 1871, who were otherwise known as the {{nihongo|'''Tōshi no Chōja'''|[[:ja:藤氏長者|藤氏長者]]}}.<ref name="Takeuchi">{{cite book|last=Takeuchi |first=Rizō |script-title=ja:律令制と貴族政権.第2部 |publisher={{Nihongo||御茶の水書房|Ocha no Mizushōbō}} |year=1958|language=Japanese }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|script-title=ja:王朝国家国政史の研究 |publisher={{Nihongo||吉川弘文館|Yoshikawa Kōbunkan}} |year=1987|language=Japanese }}</ref><ref>http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~SH8A-YMMT/hp/japan/list15.htm</ref>

The title, Tōshi no Chōja, was abolished with [[Sesshō and Kampaku]] during the [[Meiji Restoration]]; the family leaders from five main branches of the clan, known as the [[Five regent houses]], were then respectively granted with hereditary peerage titles (the ''[[kazoku]]'')<ref name="Asami">{{cite book|last=Asami |first=Masao |script-title=ja:華族誕生-名誉と体面の明治 |publisher={{Nihongo||中公文庫|Chūkō Bunko}} |year=1999 |isbn=4-12-203542-2|language=Japanese }}</ref> until the abolition of the nobility titles under the [[Constitution of Japan|new constitution]] in 1946.<ref>Lebra, ''Above the Clouds: Status Culture of the Modern Japanese Nobility''.</ref>


