==Notes==
{{noteFoot|1=
{{noteTag|name=note|1=During the [[Edo period]], some of the former royal members from [[Imperial House of Japan]] were adopted as heir to the [[Five regent houses]]. Despite having a different patrilineal descent with that of the Fujiwara clan, they and their descendants were recognized as members from Fujiwara clan instead of the Imperial House.<ref>{{cite book |last1=近藤 |first1=敏喬 |title=宮廷公家系図集覧 |date=1994 |publisher=Books Tokyodo |isbn=978-4490202434}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=幕末の宮廷 |date=1979 |publisher=平凡社 |isbn=4582803539}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ōta |first1=Akira |title=新編姓氏家系辞書 |date=1991 |publisher=秋田書店 |isbn=978-4253002639}}</ref> As such, these families are referred  as "[[:ja:皇別摂家|皇別摂家]]" in Japanese (''Kōbetsu Sekke'', "Imperial Regent Family"). <ref>{{cite web |title=皇別摂家実系系図 |url=http://www.eonet.ne.jp/~yanaken/miyasama/keizu7.htm |website=Eonet}}</ref>}}
}}

